    },
    {
      "from": "minoo@example.com",
      "to": "beatrice@example.com",
      "subject": "Re: Naphtha Shipment Inquiry",

      "body": "Hi Beatrice,\n\nIt will be possible to arrange cargo from Yanbu to Karachi. If you send me the details of your cargo, I will try to put it on charter.\n\nRegards,\nMinoo"
    },
    {
      "from": "svetlana@example.com",
      "to": "minoo@example.com",
      "subject": "Re: Naphtha Shipment Inquiry",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-02 09:00",
      "body": "Hi Minoo,\n\nBeatrice is the name of our sales manager. She mentioned in her email that her company cannot finalize freight within 48 hours of quoting. She needs to get the rate fixed within 24 hours of quoting. Please let me know if you can do this.\n\nRegards,\nSvetlana"
    },
    {
      "from": "robert@example.com",
      "to": "svetlana@example.com",
      "subject": "Re: Naphtha Shipment Inquiry",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-02 11:00",
      "body": "Dear Svetlana,\n\nFor the email you sent to Minoo, I wonder, was the information contained in that email a true reflection of what the company was looking for, or did she just request that particular bit of information?\n\nRegards,\nRobert"
    },
    {
      "from": "svetlana@example.com",
      "to": "robert@example.com",
      "subject": "Re: Naphtha Shipment Inquiry",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-02 13:00",
      "body": "Dear Robert,\n\nShe had asked for it in her last email.\n\nRegards,\nSvetlana"
    },
    {
      "from": "robert@example.com",
      "to": "svetlana@example.com",
      "subject": "Re: Naphtha Shipment Inquiry",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-02 15:00",
      "body": "Dear Svetlana,\n\nWell, that's pretty cool!\n\nI suppose I just wanted to hear it from you, directly from the horse's mouth! It just wouldn't be cricket to let it drop without asking you a few direct questions.\n\nThat little bit of information was probably something of an over-simplification, because I know for sure that it is not always possible for her to finalize freight within 24 hours of quoting.\n\nBest regards,\nRobert"
    },
    {
      "from": "robert@example.com",
      "to": "svetlana@example.com",
      "subject": "Re: Naphtha Shipment Inquiry",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-02 17:00",
      "body": "Dear Svetlana,\n\nI'd just like to say that I really appreciate you being so forthcoming with information. It has helped me to understand the situation better. So thanks for that!\n\nBest regards,\nRobert"
    },

      "from": "alice@example.com",

      "subject": "Angular 2 Input with Email Type",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-01 10:00",
      "body": "Hey Bob,\n\nNotice how the email itself doesn't go into the input? That's where everything gets tricky. If you're using input with the type of email, then you should just do the following:\n\nFor starters, if you're using Angular 2, you'll want to import FormsModule.\n\nLike so: import { FormsModule } from '@angular/forms';\nNext, you'll need to add FormsModule to the imports array in the @NgModule declaration.\n\nLike so: imports: [ BrowserModule, FormsModule ],\n\nAnd you'll need to add [email] to the input tag.\n\nThis will give you an input that looks something like this:\n\n<input type=\"email\" [(ngModel)]=\"email\">\n\nAt the end of the day, I found it quite trivial, and I suspect that most people would, too.\n\nBest,\nAlice"

{
  "email_chain": [
    {
      "from": "gavin@example.com",
      "to": "recipient@example.com",
      "subject": "Voyage Request for October 25th to 28th",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-01 09:00",
      "body": "We are looking for a voyage from October 25th to 28th for 26,000MT. Best regards, Gavin"
    },
    {
      "from": "gavin@example.com",
      "to": "recipient@example.com",
      "subject": "Voyage Request for October 25th to 28th",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-01 10:00",
      "body": "We are looking for a voyage from October 25th to 28th for 26,000MT. Best regards, Gavin"
    },
    {
      "from": "recipient@example.com",
      "to": "gavin@example.com",
      "subject": "Re: Voyage Request for October 25th to 28th",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-01 11:00",
      "body": "Dear Madame/Sir, We are looking for a voyage from October 25th to 28th for 26,000MT. To be looking for a voyage means that they need someone to buy their product. One must use the passive for this sentence. We have the object in the sentence - voyage. This can be changed to object of the preposition for - voyage for. This change turns the whole sentence into the passive sentence. The subject will be the preposition. We know this because the preposition for comes before the subject. We can make it a voyage. We are looking for a voyage."
    },
    {
      "from": "recipient@example.com",
      "to": "gavin@example.com",
      "subject": "Re: Voyage Request for October 25th to 28th",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-01 12:00",
      "body": "Who are looking for a voyage? Answer: They are looking for a voyage. Common mistake in student papers: 1. Using the active form for these sentences. We do not use the active form when there is a preposition after the subject. It should be He is looking for a house. We have the active form He is looking, but for comes after it. We change the active form to the passive form, thus creating the passive form. There is looking for a house. 2. Removing the article. The article a is required to make the sentence active. He is looking for a house. If you remove a, you have created a passive sentence. Who is looking?"
    }
  ],

      "body": "Hi Michael,\n\nHope you are well.\n\nAs far as Mundra is concerned, there will be no berth congestion (whether it be monthly or weekly) in any month of this year. Regarding the port of Long Beach, the container volume is consistently increasing month on month. It will also increase in the coming month. However, we can see that in February 2019, there were 8 ETDs, whereas in January 2019 there were 7 ETDs. The transshipment movement from West Africa & other major US destinations to Long Beach will increase by more than 10% this year. Hence we may see less berth congestion in the months of January, February & March 2019. However, the probability of berth congestion in April and onward months is very high as long as the CBP do not relax any of their existing regulations to reduce the dwell time.\n\nBest regards,\nPeter"

      "timestamp": "2019-01-18 11:45",
      "body": "Hi Michael,\n\nKindly note the following changes in view of the proposed cut off:\n\n- All STS, which were used in the past to eliminate congestion, will cease by end of March 2019.\n- Due to many more factors like larger volume, berth congestion & diversification, the terminal now prefers containers which are loaded onto wagons, trucks, rail heads, special containers (Transponders, Chilled, Refrigerated, etc.) as well as containers which are to be exported via Ocean Terminal, Pier 400, Long Beach Container Terminal (LBCT), ...\n- Longer term (year on year), the terminal hopes that it will be able to achieve more in terms of more Gate out/container return, which is the only way the terminal will be able to handle more volume.\n\nBest regards,\nPeter"

{
  "email_chain": [
    {
      "from": "bob@example.com",
      "to": "x@example.com",
      "subject": "Charter Request for Petroleum Coke Transport",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-01 09:00",
      "body": "Hello X,\n\nWe want to charter a vessel to transport 2000 MT of petroleum coke from Baku to Qingdao, China. Do you have any ship available in November?\n\nRegards,\nBob"
    },
    {
      "from": "x@example.com",
      "to": "bob@example.com",
      "subject": "Re: Charter Request for Petroleum Coke Transport",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-01 10:00",
      "body": "Hello Bob,\n\nBest price on spot by sea transport:\n- 0.19 $/MT\n- 0.05 $/MT bunker\n\nDetails:\n1. Charter party done on GLS\n2. Cargo: Petroleum coke - 20,000 MT\n3. B/L paid - 100%\n4. Sailing in November\n5. From Baku, Azerbaijan to Qingdao, China\n\nBest Regards,\nX"
    },
    {
      "from": "bob@example.com",
      "to": "x@example.com",
      "subject": "Re: Charter Request for Petroleum Coke Transport",
      "timestamp": "2023-10-01 11:00",
      "body": "The main trick is to make this task look like it is for open charter. This makes the victim pay attention to the price, believing it is actually lower than the price of the chartered ship (by the way, let's make it 0.19 $/MT). By saying that you will pay 0.05 $/MT for bunker, the victim thinks you are buying bunker, while you are actually renting the vessel.\n\nAlso note that the shipping cost (0.19 $/MT) is given to the nearest part of the fourth decimal place, which might look suspicious if the sender and receiver have different countries. It is a very good trick to make such mistakes, as I did in email 2, or even in email 1 if the victim is inexperienced. It makes the victim think he is comparing two similar offers, which they are not, and look bad for not noticing it.\n\nBest Regards,\nBob"
    }

      "body": "Actually, there’s an alternative – the business needn’t try to find out whether the lumber is in compliance with U.S. law, but simply can certify to that effect.
